04545nam a22006855i 9780271085296DE-B159720230328044521.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230328t20192019pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710852967 a10.1515/97802710852962doi  a(DE-B1597)584558  a(OCoLC)1262307474  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aLAN0150002bisacsh1 aCherney, James L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRSA Series in Transdisciplinary Rhetoric. Ableist Rhetoric :bHow We Know, Value, and See Disability /cJames L. Cherney. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRSA Series in Transdisciplinary Rhetoric ;v1100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 The Rhetorical Dimensions of Ableism -- t2 Fearing Disability and the Possession Narrative -- t3 Ableism and the Cochlear Implant Debate -- t4 Sport as Ableist Institution -- t5 A Rhetorical Model of Disability -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAbleism, a form of discrimination that elevates “able” bodies over those perceived as less capable, remains one of the most widespread areas of systematic and explicit discrimination in Western culture. Yet in contrast to the substantial body of scholarly work on racism, sexism, classism, and heterosexism, ableism remains undertheorized and underexposed. In this book, James L. Cherney takes a rhetorical approach to the study of ableism to reveal how it has worked its way into our everyday understanding of disability.Ableist Rhetoric argues that ableism is learned and transmitted through the ways we speak about those with disabilities. Through a series of textual case studies, Cherney identifies three rhetorical norms that help illustrate the widespread influence of ableist ideas in society. He explores the notion that “deviance is evil” by analyzing the possession narratives of Cotton Mather and the modern horror touchstone The Exorcist. He then considers whether “normal is natural” in Aristotle’s Generation of Animals and in the cultural debate over cochlear implants. Finally, he shows how the norm “body is able” operates in Alexander Graham Bell’s writings on eugenics and in the legal cases brought by disabled athletes Casey Martin and Oscar Pistorius. These three simple equivalencies play complex roles within the social institutions of religion, medicine, law, and sport. Cherney concludes by calling for a rhetorical model of disability, which, he argues, will provide a shift in orientation to challenge ableism’s epistemic, ideological, and visual components. Accessible and compelling, this groundbreaking book will appeal to scholars of rhetoric and of disability studies as well as to disability rights advocates.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Rhetoric.2bisacsh  aAbleism.  aAbleist Culture.  aDisability.  aDiscrimination.  aRhetoric.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311074520740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978027108529640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271085296423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271085296/original  a978-3-11-074520-7  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK